F-centers are crystallographic defects that arise from the presence of vacancies or interstitial atoms in a crystal lattice. They are responsible for imparting color to many minerals and crystals, and the colors can range from pale yellow to deep red or blue depending on the concentration and distribution of F-centers. The presence of F-centers can also affect the physical and mechanical properties of a crystal. The presence of F-Centers in a material affects its appearance in two ways: 
(1) It increases the amount of light reflected from the surface of a material; 
(2) It decreases the ability of light to pass through a material. This means that if you are looking at a material through F-Centers, you should be able to see objects behind it but not as well as if there were no F-Centers present
